FedLogic: Interpretable Federated Multi-Domain Chain-of-Thought Prompt Selection for Large Language Models

Pengwei Xing1, Songtao Lu2, Han Yu1
Abstract

Leveraging â€œchain-of-thought (CoT)â€ reasoning to elicit rapid and precise responses from large language models (LLMs) is rapidly attracting research interest. A notable challenge here is how to design or select optimal prompts. The process of prompt selection relies on trial and error, involving continuous adjustments and combinations of input prompts by users based on the corresponding new responses generated from LLMs. Furthermore, minimal research has been conducted to explore how LLMs employ the mathematical problem-solving capabilities learned from user interactions to address issues in narrative writing. To improve interpretability and explore the balance principle between generality and personalization under a multi-domain CoT prompt selection scenario, we propose the Federated Logic rule learning approach (FedLogic). We introduce a theoretical formalization and interactive emulation of the multi-domain CoT prompt selection dilemma in the context of federated LLMs. We cast the problem of joint probability modeling as a bilevel program, where the CoT prompt selection intricacy can be likened to a fuzzy score-based rule selection with the LLMs function as rule generators. FedLogic solves this problem through variational expectation maximization (V-EM). In addition, we incorporate two KL-divergence constraints within this probabilistic modeling framework to surmount the intricacies of managing extensive search spaces and accomplishing cross-domain personalization of CoTs. To the best of our knowledge, FedLogic is the first interpretable and principled federated multi-domain CoT prompt selection approach for LLMs.

Introduction

In recent years, the rapid advancement of natural language processing (NLP) technologies has led to the emergence of large language models (LLMs), such as GPT-3 (Brown etÂ al. 2020) (Generative Pre-trained Transformer 3) and its variants. Their ability to generate coherent and contextually relevant responses has sparked significant interest and enthusiasm in both academia and industry. The underlying mechanism that drives the impressive performance of LLMs lies in their capacity to capture intricate patterns and relationships in vast amounts of textual data. The result is the strong ability to mimic human-like language use and generate plausible texts in a wide range of contexts.

Despite their success, LLMs remain black-boxes in terms of understanding their internal processes and decision-making rationale. The parameters of the top performing LLMs are not available to the public either. This has led to the current LLM research landscape with the majority of the effort focusing on black-box-injection work without formal theory. In-context learning(Brown etÂ al. 2020) (ICL) has been researched in few-shot learning (Min etÂ al. 2022, 2021) in the early stage and recently is being used to describe this mainstream technique for improving LLMs models based on open-domain text (Chowdhery etÂ al. 2022; Zhang etÂ al. 2022), in contrast to the previous BERT-based methods (Devlin etÂ al. 2018) where fine-tuning of model parameters was the prevailing approach. Most of the existing ICL works are interfacing with different kinds of learning tasks (Garg etÂ al. 2022; Laskin etÂ al. 2022; MÃ¼ller etÂ al. 2021) and implicit properties (Xie etÂ al. 2021; Chan etÂ al. 2022).

The chain-of-thought (CoT) is a representative research pillar of the field of ICL. It injects the inferred steps of the natural language description associated with the problem into LLMs along with the labels to enhance tasks with high inferential demands (Wei etÂ al. 2022). Gao etÂ al. 2023 injects the code descriptions associated with the inference and subsequently when relaying a code runtime to obtain more accurate results. Multi-prompt ensemble-based research has also emerged to ensure answer consistency (Wang etÂ al. 2022). Prompt selection has branched out into a variety of approaches under ICL, including prompt tuning with a prompt-target parameter (Lester, Al-Rfou, and Constant 2021), leveraging separated LLMs to select prompt (Zhou etÂ al. 2022), and reinforcement learning based prompt selection (Su etÂ al. 2022). The aforementioned study has empirically verified the effectiveness of CoTs.

However, the prevailing approach for CoT prompt selection is through trial and error. The process typically involves continuous adjustments and combinations of input prompts by users based on the corresponding new responses generated by LLMs (Yang etÂ al. 2022; AkyÃ¼rek etÂ al. 2023). Moreover, there is limited investigation on how LLMs utilize the mathematical problem-solving CoTs inference ability acquired from user interactions to provide CoTs answer for the domain of narrative composition. It involves a cross-domain and one-to-many federated trade-off between the specificity and generality of the logical abilities of LLMs.

To bridge this gap, we propose the Federated Logic rule learning approach (FedLogic) for multi-domain LLM CoT prompt selection. It is a first-of-its-kind transformer-based in-context learner designed to simultaneously provide a principled approach for multi-domain LLM CoT prompt selection while enhancing the interpretability and adaptability of LLMs. Cross domain in-context learning requires LLMs to balance generalization with specialization. This problem can be solved by applying a new variational distribution that transforms the general latent variance probability model into a specialized latent variance probability model. This is equivalent to solving a non-i.i.d. federated learning (FL) (Tan etÂ al. 2022) optimization problem when CoTs come from multiple non-i.i.d. domain. We design the transformer as a latent-variance logic rule learner, and formalize the CoTs as logic rules. The transformer-based rule learner competes with the CoTs rule selector in the manner of bilevel learning with variational expectation maximization (V-EM) (Tzikas, Likas, and Galatsanos 2008). This framework leverages two Kullbackâ€“Leibler (KL) divergence based constraints in a probabilistic modeling perspective to address the challenges of the large search space and cross-domain personalization of CoTs.

To the best of our knowledge, FedLogic is the first interpretable and principled multi-domain CoT prompt selection approach supporting federated LLMs. In experiment, we focus on exploring the cross-domain CoT representational ability on a designed dataset under cross-visible distribution among different clients to understand how LLMs use the mathematical CoT reference ability to generate narrative composition CoTs. We also extend the state-of-the-art baseline from (Ru etÂ al. 2021) to handle one-to-many complexities equivalently. Extensive experiments demonstrate our modelâ€™s superior performance even when the baseline has been further optimized. Our design to leverage KL-divergence has led to enhanced outcomes on both seen and unseen data. Additionally, we undertake a thorough evaluation of our modelâ€™s inference capabilities through simulations on real data, using golden first-order logical predicates. The results demonstrate its effectiveness in providing interpretable multi-domain CoT prompt selection for LLMs in a federated manner.

The Proposed FedLogic Approach

In this paper, we focus on the application scenario of federated multi-domain CoT prompt selection. We assume that there is a pool of CoT prompts from multiple domains accumulated from previous interactions with LLMs. When a user wishes to interact with the LLMs, he/she first has to select the CoT prompt from the prompt pool which best suits his/her task. Instead of trial and error, the user can query the CoT prompt pool based on his/her local data (which is potentially sensitive and requires data privacy protection). The FedLogic serves as an approach to accomplish such a search and matching task in an explainable manner.

Without loss of generality, we assume that the ICL query-answer system is a one-to-many bilevel system. The in-context learner is on the upper-level (FL server) side, and the example of query, CoTs, and labels come from multiple lower-level (FL client) sides. nğ‘›n denotes the number of clients. This is because when the examples of multiple lower-level sides are independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.), the CoTs belong to the same domain. This is equivalent to traditional single-domain ICL. When each lower-level side handles a non-i.i.d. task, the CoTs are from multiple different domains. This setting enables us to study the interplay between generalization and personalization in ICL.

Since CoTs are the sequence of reasoning steps, it is natural to treat them as logic rules. We formalize a CoT rule as a latent variable zğ‘§z. Algorithm Design for FedLogic

The details of the overall bi-level based CoTs (rule) selection approach of FedLogic is shown in AlgorithmÂ 1. In Line 5 and Line 12, the algorithm only transmits the rule probability values and the new rules between each FL client and the FL server. In Lines 13-14, the server generates samples from the received posterior distribution, and adds them to the training set for the server model to access client information. Similarly, in Lines 5-7), each client only receives the new rules to initialize the weight and update wisubscriptğ‘¤ğ‘–w_{i}. None of them need direct access to each otherâ€™s data, which is in line with the requirement of federated learning.

Experimental Evaluation

Experiment Settings

Dataset.

To comprehensively evaluate the performance of FedLogic, we utilize a document-level DWIE (Document-Level Web Information Extraction) dataset (Zaporojets etÂ al. 2021) that has been pre-processed following the methods outlined in (Ru etÂ al. 2021). This dataset contains detailed word type statistics, particularly named entity recognition (NER) categories, for all selected entity words within news articles. It encompasses 101010 different NER categories. The dataset also features annotated relationships between entities, spanning a total of 656565 relationship categories. We leverage these relation annotations among entities to formulate a relation prediction task.

The dataset comprises 799799799 documents in total, categorized into 101010 NER types. These documents are distributed across 444 FL clients, with each client containing 200200200 documents, except for the last client, which holds 199199199 documents. Within each client, the documents are further divided into training and testing subsets, maintaining a 3:1:313:1 ratio.

Cross-Domain Testing Setup.

we design a cross-visible distribution multi-domain testing setup to investigate how LLMs utilize the mathematical problem-solving CoTs inference ability acquired from user interactions to give the CoTs answer for the domain of narrative composition. To be specific, each client is equipped with three distinct sub-datasets: a seen training set, a seen testing set, and an unseen set. Notably, the distribution of the unseen set differs from that of the seen sets and is excluded from model training. Meanwhile, each clientâ€™s unseen testing data has same distribution with the seen training data in the neighboring clients. For this, we partition the 101010 NER categories into two groups, each containing 555 categories. These categories are subsequently cross-combined to yield 444 unique category combinations, aligned with the 444 head-tail combinations for the 444 clients, respectively. A key aspect of our approach involves ensuring that each clientâ€™s seen set is misaligned with the unseen set by one category. This means that each clientâ€™s unseen testing data is the seen training data in the neighboring clients. This strategy results in the creation of 444 non-i.i.d. datasets, each characterized by different head-tail NER category combinations. A clientâ€™s seen rule representation can help build other clientsâ€™ unseen rule representations.

Learning Task.

The primary experimental task is to emulate the question-and-answer process of LLMs using CoTs centered around knowledge graph (KG) relationship prediction. Within this context, a âŸ¨h,?,tâŸ©â„?ğ‘¡\langle h,?,t\rangle structure alongside its associated rğ‘Ÿr (rhâ€‹eâ€‹aâ€‹dsubscriptğ‘Ÿâ„ğ‘’ğ‘ğ‘‘r_{head}) within a KG triplet corresponds to a question-and-answer scenario mimicking user-LLM interactions. Importantly, all feasible paths connecting hâ„h to tğ‘¡t serve as CoTs, symbolizing the logical rule bodies to be acquired.

As illustrated in FigureÂ 1, the knowledge graph relations are mapped from the semantic domain to the named entity recognition (NER) domain. In the semantic space, the elementary unit is rğ‘Ÿr (rhâ€‹eâ€‹aâ€‹dsubscriptğ‘Ÿâ„ğ‘’ğ‘ğ‘‘r_{head}), determined by a specific head node and tail node. Through projection into the NER space, the fundamental element becomes a path (rule body), contingent on the NER attributes of both the head and tail nodes, in addition to the intermediary rhâ€‹eâ€‹aâ€‹dsubscriptğ‘Ÿâ„ğ‘’ğ‘ğ‘‘r_{head} relation. To illustrate, in FigureÂ 1(b), employing the amalgamation of the red NER category, green category, and relation ağ‘a (rule head) as the query within the NER space, multiple feasible paths [(b,c),(e,a,c)]ğ‘ğ‘ğ‘’ğ‘ğ‘[(b,c),(e,a,c)] are associated with ağ‘a. These rule bodies, along with the corresponding NER query, emulate user inputs akin to CoTs for LLMs, as depicted in FigureÂ 1(a).

Due to the non-uniqueness of rule bodies, it becomes imperative to employ a stochastic optimization model for learning the latent variables within the NER space. As demonstrated in FigureÂ 1 (c), at the upper level, a transformer-based rule generator is harnessed to learn and produce numerous potential paths (rule bodies). These generated candidates are subsequently disseminated to the lower-level rule selector. This design choice mitigates the necessity for extensive local search operations to uncover paths within a vast search space. For LLMs, this translates to users being spared the ordeal of iteratively composing CoTs and, instead, directly accessing effective CoTs by a small selection of choices furnished by the LLMs through personalized local knowledge, as depicted in FigureÂ 1 (c).

The Upper-Level Model.

For the upper-level rule generator, we employ a transformer-based model. The role of the rule generator is to utilize the query path rğ‘Ÿr to sequentially generate each relation within the equivalent path r1âˆ§â‹¯âˆ§rlsubscriptğ‘Ÿ1â‹¯subscriptğ‘Ÿğ‘™r_{1}\wedge\dots\wedge r_{l}. The transformer architecture, renowned for its efficacy in generating sequential outputs such as translations (Vaswani etÂ al. 2017), proves fitting for this task. Additionally, it provides a probability measure of rule generation.

To realize the transition from pÎ¸subscriptğ‘ğœƒp_{\theta} to p~Î¸subscript~ğ‘ğœƒ\tilde{p}_{\theta} within the upper-level objective function of Eq.Â (5), involving the projection into the NER (logic) space, a novel approach is designed. Instead of only inputting the rule head rğ‘Ÿr embedding into a conventional transformer-based model, the embeddings of the NER categories for the head and tail nodes are also incorporated. These embeddings are amalgamated with the rğ‘Ÿr embedding to form the input embedding for the transformer. This strategic inclusion of the head-tail NER embeddings empowers the transformer-based model to project into the NER rule space. This, in turn, signifies a transformation from a general transformer-based next-word learner into a transformer-based rule generator, as exemplified in the upper level of FigureÂ 1(c). It mirrors the progression from the general state to an in-context session within LLMs, as depicted in the upper level of FigureÂ 1(a).

The Lower-Level Model.

The local modelâ€™s responsibility is straightforward. Upon the upper-level rule generator producing Nğ‘N potential rule bodies, the local model employs the label of the rule head to update wisubscriptğ‘¤ğ‘–w_{i}. This update facilitates the selection of the optimal rule body for rhâ€‹eâ€‹aâ€‹dsubscriptğ‘Ÿâ„ğ‘’ğ‘ğ‘‘r_{head}, and entails traversing each rğ‘Ÿr from 111 to lğ‘™l along the path of this rule body r1âˆ§â‹¯âˆ§rlsubscriptğ‘Ÿ1â‹¯subscriptğ‘Ÿğ‘™r_{1}\wedge\dots\wedge r_{l}. Subsequently, a pre-trained embedding value derived from (Zhou etÂ al. 2021) is employed as the corresponding fuzzy values. These values serve to derive a fresh score for rhâ€‹eâ€‹aâ€‹dsubscriptğ‘Ÿâ„ğ‘’ğ‘ğ‘‘r_{head}. This process emulates LLM usersâ€™ evaluation of the LLMsâ€™ answer CoTs and their subsequent feedback regarding the perceived correct answer (FigureÂ 1).

Cross-Domain Personalization between Upper Level and Lower Level.

An additional noteworthy concern illustrated in FigureÂ 1 necessitates resolution between the upper-level and lower-level models. Specifically, the challenge pertains to the non-i.i.d. nature of CoTs across domains. Merging CoTs or rules from divergent distributions within the same server model does not guarantee effective representation learning for rules across disparate distributions. Alternatively, rules commonly learned by a universal server might not be suitable for specific user contexts. To address this, a KL-divergence term is incorporated as a regularization mechanism into the lower-level objective function. This strategic integration facilitates a balance between the extent of generalization and specialization for the rule model.

Model Setup.

The transformer model at the server encodes NER categories and relations through unique numerical identifiers. The embedding layer size for relations is (256,2â€‹R+1)2562ğ‘…1(256,2R+1), with Rğ‘…R representing the number of relations (65 in this case). Similarly, the NER category embedding layer has dimensions (256,10)25610(256,10), reflecting the 10 distinct NER categories. The model contains two encoding and decoding layers, and an output layer of size (256,2â€‹R+1)2562ğ‘…1(256,2R+1). The input for the transformer is obtained by concatenating a rule head and a rule body, both of size 4. Any shortfall is supplemented with padding symbols and masked using a 4Ã—4444\times 4 position mask. Each rule head generates a set of 50 rule bodies on average, and these candidates are then transmitted to the lower-level model, with duplicates removed.

On the client side, the rule selector model dynamically initializes the weights for each communication round. These weights are tailored to the candidate rule bodies originating from the upper level, with their variability stemming from the stochastic nature of the upper-level optimization process and the probabilistic characteristics of the generated rules. The weight group size is denoted as (K,NÃ—1)ğ¾ğ‘1(K,N\times 1), where Kğ¾K is the number of rule head categories. Each weight group member corresponds to a candidate rule body, with its dimensions as NÃ—1ğ‘1N\times 1. The value of Nğ‘N is not fixed due to the exclusion of duplicate candidate rule bodies.

Results and Discussion

In order to conduct a rigorous assessment, we extend the state-of-the-art baseline of (Ru etÂ al. 2021) from traditional one-to-one to handle one-to-many complexities equivalently to investigate the role of the KL divergence with probability-based constraints between the upper and lower levels. In scenarios where rule-based decision-making is employed, the local model can exhibit oscillations and fail to converge due to the dynamic nature of the process. The inclusion of a KL divergence constraint mitigates this phenomenon. Evaluation of overall performance is based on metrics averaged across all clients. We compare the outcomes of two sets of experiments using F1-scores on both the Unseen and Seen testing data. â€œW/O. KLâ€ and â€œW. KLâ€ denote experiments conducted without (the method of (Ru etÂ al. 2021)) and with KL-divergence constraints (FedLogic), respectively.

The results in FigureÂ 2 show that introducing a KL-divergence constraint to both the Seen and Unseen testing data groups leads to convergence at higher F1-scores. Conversely, the Unseen testing data group without KL-divergence adjustment achieves convergence but at lower F1-scores. The Seen testing data group without KL-divergence constraint exhibits oscillations and does not achieve convergence under the same conditions. Additionally, we analyze the impact of varying KL coefficients on F1 score results for the Unseen dataset. The results in FigureÂ 3 demonstrate that different coefficients indeed influence the personalization performance.

To assess the logical reasoning capabilities of FedLogic, we adopt the 39 golden first-order logic predicates from the DWIE dataset (Zaporojets etÂ al. 2021) for consistency checks after updates by the rule selector model in the lower level, following (Ru etÂ al. 2021). FedLogic vs. Neural-Symbolic Learning.

The most related works from neural symbol learning are (Ru etÂ al. 2021) and (Qu etÂ al. 2020). The problem for both of them can be denoted as pwâ€‹(a|z,q,ğ’¢)â€‹pÎ¸â€‹(z|q)subscriptğ‘ğ‘¤conditionalğ‘ğ‘§ğ‘ğ’¢subscriptğ‘ğœƒconditionalğ‘§ğ‘{p_{w}(a|z,q,\mathcal{G})p_{\theta}(z|q)}, while our problem is defined in Eq.Â (The Proposed FedLogic Approach). Comparing these two formulations, there are two major differences. Firstly, our problem is one-to-many rather compared to their one-to-one problem scenario. Secondly, our hidden variable is jointly inferred with queries from nğ‘›n clients (i.e., ğ’›|âˆªi=1nqi)\boldsymbol{z}|\cup_{i=1}^{n}q_{i}) in contrast to their hidden variable z|qconditionalğ‘§ğ‘z|q). Note that under the FL setting, the non-i.i.d. issue is common. Therefore, our work is better suited for practical FL scenarios.

Conclusions

In this paper, we proposed a first-of-its-kind rule-based one-to-many transformer-based in-context learning approach enabling users with sensitive local data to collaboratively learn how to select the most appropriate CoT prompts. It enhances the interpretability of LLMs from the perspective of up-down interactions, in contrast to previous works which solely focused on the role of the transformer. In addition, our approach expands the horizon of FL research, empowering researchers to address the challenge of model fusion in decision-making tasks with dynamic weights, as well as tackling the non-i.i.d. problem by modeling the server rule decisions as probabilistic hidden variables. Our framework is a novel one-to-many approach, distinguishing itself from traditional one-to-one neural symbolic reasoning systems.

Optimizing the Fuzzy Function for Posterior

In this section, we strive to enhance our algorithm by refining the optimization process of the fuzzy function. Drawing from Algorithm 1, at the lower level, we utilize eq.(ICL with Cross Domain CoTs) as the objective function for updating wisubscriptğ‘¤ğ‘–w_{i}. The posterior segment of eq.(ICL with Cross Domain CoTs) is calculated using eq.Â (12). Before employing label aisubscriptğ‘ğ‘–a_{i} to generate the new posterior, a fuzzy function is applied to the distributed rule bodies from the server. This function calculates the fuzzy score for each rule body (maxğ’¢â€‹iâ€‹âˆkâˆˆlâ€‹xâ€‹(rkâ€‹j)subscriptğ’¢ğ‘–productğ‘˜ğ‘™ğ‘¥subscriptğ‘Ÿğ‘˜ğ‘—\max_{\mathcal{G}i}\prod{k\in l}x(r_{kj})) by maximizing across the entirety of ğ’¢isubscriptğ’¢ğ‘–\mathcal{G}_{i}. Given the time-intensive nature of this step, optimizing the fuzzy function becomes necessary.

The core concept revolves around utilizing eq.Â (12) solely for computing the posterior during the initial Iğ¼I communication rounds, aiming to establish a fundamental rule generator. In subsequent stages, an innovatively designed path-based fuzzy posterior score function is adopted, replacing the graph-based fuzzy function (maxğ’¢â€‹iâ€‹âˆkâˆˆlâ€‹xâ€‹(rkâ€‹j)subscriptğ’¢ğ‘–productğ‘˜ğ‘™ğ‘¥subscriptğ‘Ÿğ‘˜ğ‘—\max_{\mathcal{G}i}\prod{k\in l}x(r_{kj})) for saving computational time. Time Complexity Analysis for Cross-Domain Learning

In this section, we first provide an example to showcase the essence of cross-domain learning (FL) under our experiment scenario. As shown in FigureÂ 1(a), using the relation ağ‘a in triplet <5,a,6><5,a,6> as an instance, our goal is to improve the prediction accuracy of relation ağ‘a by finding more new rule bodies (equivalent paths from node 5 to node 6) to infer and update the fuzzy value of rule head ağ‘a. There are two equivalent paths from node 5 to node 6 in domain 1, (b,c)ğ‘ğ‘(b,c) and (e,a,c)ğ‘’ğ‘ğ‘(e,a,c), while there are also two paths (b,c)ğ‘ğ‘(b,c) and (f,h)ğ‘“â„(f,h) in domain 2, which include a different path (f,h)ğ‘“â„(f,h) that can enable us to obtain new information from another domain. We know that increasing the diversity of samples reduces the error rate and thus improves the accuracy of relationship prediction.

If we want to update all fuzzy values for all edges across these two domains by discovering new equivalent edges, we have the following four options:

  • â€¢

    Deterministic Graph Aggregation

    In this baseline approach, the adjacency matrix and fuzzy values of both domain 1 and domain 2 are transmitted to the server. Subsequently, the server merges the adjacency matrices to create a larger dimensional adjacency matrix along with corresponding relations. The most time-intensive phase is the path search within the merged graph space.

  • â€¢

    Deterministic Rule Aggregation

    In this baseline approach, the time-consuming stage involves performing an intra-domain maximum weight path search for each domain (domain 1 and domain 2) using the agreed-upon uniform NER-pair query pair as the start and end points. The resulting paths are then merged on the server based on the uniform NER-pair query pair.

  • â€¢

    Stochastic Rule Aggregation (AlgorithmÂ 1)

    In AlgorithmÂ 1, an intra-domain path search is confined to paths distributed from the server. This implies that the head-tail pairs are fewer than those in the deterministic rule aggregation approach. Nonetheless, a smaller-scale path search is still necessary.

  • â€¢

    Stochastic Rule Aggregation (AlgorithmÂ 2)

    For AlgorithmÂ 2, a limited intra-domain path search is only required during the initial Iğ¼I rounds.

Sensitivity of adding ratio of posterior sample for upper-level training

To examine whether the incorporation of posterior samples obtained from the lower-level (E-step) can effectively impact the upper-level rule updates in the M-step, we conducted a total of 9 experiments ranging from a sample inclusion ratio of 10%percent1010\% to 90%percent9090\% as shown in the FigureÂ 7. This comparison aimed to assess the varying effects of different ratios on the training loss of the upper-level rule trainer during its first round of training.

The results indicate that a mere increase in the inclusion ratio of posterior samples from 10%percent1010\% to 20%percent2020\% has a substantial effect in reducing the training loss of the upper-level model. Subsequently, as this ratio is uniformly raised, the loss continues to decrease, albeit at a progressively slower rate. The improvement in the upper-level model becomes less pronounced after incorporating around 70%percent7070\% of the posterior samples. This phenomenon provides evidence for the effectiveness of posterior samples in enhancing the upper-level model. The limited impact observed with higher ratios is consistent with the principle that a certain proportion of samples can effectively reflect the contained posterior information; an excessive number of samples could lead to information redundancy.

Sensitivity of upper-level learning rate

In this experiment, we conducted tests using three sets of different learning rates for the upper-level rule learner under two conditions: with KL-divergence constraint and without KL-divergence constraint. These tests were performed on both Seen and Unseen test data to evaluate the impact of the rule generator on the overall game system. As depicted in FigureÂ 8, we observe three phenomena:

  • â€¢

    The first phenomenon is that KL dominance occurs only when the upper level achieves dominance in the upper-lower level game, i.e., a larger upper-lower learning rate. This observation aligns with our formulaâ€™s implication that when the lower levelâ€™s specialization abilities are in agreement, the group with stronger generalization ability can learn more global prior knowledge at the given learning rate. Consequently, this leads to enhanced overall performance. In cases of insufficient learning rate, the upper-level learning fails to acquire adequate information about the global prior to using the global generalization ability.

  • â€¢

    The second phenomenon is that while the overall F1 value and the overall logic value increase as the upper learning rate increase, the curves of logic accuracy and F1 only exhibit greater consistency when the learning rate is sufficiently high. This finding indicates that the upper level is indeed learning effective rules to improve the overall F1 performance. When the rule learner fails to learn sufficiently, the rules newly distributed from the upper level may not necessarily be effective for the lower level.

  • â€¢

    The third phenomenon is that the gap between the curves corresponding to the two groups, Unseen and Seen, is smaller when the upper layer model employs a lower learning rate. This effect is evident when the upper layer is disadvantaged in the game between the upper and lower layers. This behavior can be observed in both subplots of the F1 values corresponding to (a1) and the logic accuracy values corresponding to (b1), with the latter curve in (b1) almost overlapping. This phenomenon implies that the upper model can differentially generate rules for the Unseen and Seen data, and as this role weakens, the difference between the curves of Seen and Unseen data becomes smaller.
